Simulation Procedure

The FIR digital filter module was designed using Verilog HDL.
A separate testbench was created to apply sequential input samples.
Behavioral simulation was run in Xilinx Vivado.
Waveforms were observed to verify correct filtering operation and output generation.

=========================================================================================================================================================
Waveform Analysis

The waveform shows the operation of the FIR digital filter during different clock cycles.
Initially, the output signal y[15:0] remains undefined (XXXX) because the filter registers do not yet contain previous input samples required for filtering operation.
As the clock signal toggles, input samples such as 01, 02, 03, 04, 05, and 06 are applied sequentially to the filter. 
The filter stores previous samples internally and performs moving average filtering to generate smooth output values.
After sufficient input samples are received, valid output values such as 0014, 001E, and 0028 are generated. 
The gradual change in output values confirms the smoothing behavior of the FIR filter. The waveform also verifies correct sample shifting, clock synchronization, and sequential processing of input data.
Overall, the waveform demonstrates proper FIR filter functionality and synchronous digital signal processing operation.

